    comment: '<p><code>em</code> is directly proportional to the font size currently in use. This makes it easier to keep the proportions intact for future changes and responsive design.</p>\n<p>With <code>px</code> :</p>\n<pre><code class="language-css">.bodytext p {\n    font-size:14px;\n}\n.image {\n    width:80px;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>Or, using <code>em</code> :</p>\n<pre><code class="language-css">.bodytext p {\n    font-size:0.875em; /* 16x.875=14 */\n}\n.sidenote {\n    font-size:5em; /* 16x5=80 */\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>Another advantage of <code>em</code> relates to a browser\'s support for custom font sizes (which can override your CSS). These custom sizes could break a layout if the font sizes are in <code>px</code>.</p>\n',
